# Rule Name: Languages
Description: This rule describes which languages should be used and when to use each.

## Core Technologies
- Use only HTML, SCSS, and JavaScript
- Use SCSS instead of pure CSS
  - We have an automatic SCSS -> CSS compiler cursor extension
- Keep the codebase lightweight and maintainable
- Favor HTML and SCSS solutions over JavaScript when possible

## HTML Guidelines
- Use semantic HTML5 elements appropriately
- Structure content logically and hierarchically
- Ensure proper accessibility with ARIA attributes when needed
- Keep markup clean and meaningful

✅ Good:
```html
<header>
  <nav>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
      <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
</header>
<main>
  <article>
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <section>
      <h2>Section Heading</h2>
      <p>Content goes here...</p>
    </section>
  </article>
</main>
<footer>
  <p>&copy; 2024 Company Name</p>
</footer>
```

❌ Bad:
```html
<div class="header">
  <div class="nav">
    <div class="menu">
      <div>Home</div>
      <div>About</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="content">
  <div class="article">
    <div class="title">Article Title</div>
    <!-- Avoid non-semantic divs -->
  </div>
</div>
```

## Implementation Priority
1. Start with semantic HTML structure
2. Style with SCSS
3. Add JavaScript only when necessary for:
   - Complex user interactions
   - Dynamic data handling
   - Features impossible with HTML/CSS alone

## Best Practices
- Ensure progressive enhancement
- Maintain accessibility
- Optimize performance
- Test across browsers
- Keep code simple and maintainable